{{Distinguish2|[[Karl Steubl]] from [[Sobibór extermination camp]]}} {{Infobox military person |name=Karl Streibel |image=Karl Streibel KL Trawniki.jpg |image_size=280 |caption=Karl Streibel at [[Trawniki concentration camp|Trawniki]] (with potbelly, smiling) inspects the company of [[Ukrainische Hilfspolizei|Hiwis]] (some still wearing Soviet Budionovkas) |birth_date=11 October 1903 |death_date=1986<ref>Dieter Pohl: ''Von der "Judenpolitik" zum Judenmord. Der Distrikt des Generalgouvernements 1939-1944.'' Lang, Frankfurt 1993, p. 186</ref> |birth_place=[[Chiemgau]], [[Upper Bavaria]], [[German Empire]] |death_place= |allegiance={{flagicon|Nazi Germany}} [[Nazi Germany]] |branch=[[File:Flag Schutzstaffel.svg|23px]] [[Schutzstaffel]] |serviceyears=until 1945 |rank=[[Sturmbannführer]] |unit=[[File:3rd SS Division Logo.svg|23px]] [[SS-Totenkopfverbände]] }} ''[[SS-Hauptsturmführer]]'' '''Karl Streibel''' (11 October 1903 – 1986) was the second and last commander of the [[Trawniki concentration camp]] – one of the subcamps of the [[KL Lublin]] system of [[Nazi concentration camps]] in [[occupied Poland]] during World War II.<ref name="Jabłoński">{{cite web | url=http://www.trawniki.hg.pl/traw/obozjab.html | title=Hitlerowski obóz w Trawnikach | publisher=Trawniki official website | work=The camp history | accessdate=2013-04-30 | author=Mgr Stanisław Jabłoński (1927&ndash;2002) | language=Polish}}</ref>
Streibel was born in the area of [[Chiemgau]] in [[Oberbayern]] (Upper Bavaria). He joined the [[NSDAP]] and the [[SS]] at the age of 29, in November 1932. He was promoted to ''Obersturmführer'' just before the Nazi German [[invasion of Poland]]. He was appointed leader of Trawniki by [[Odilo Globocnik|Globocnik]] on 27 October 1941 to conduct training of the collaborationist [[auxiliary police]] a.k.a. "[[Hiwi (volunteer)|Hiwi]]s" (''Hilfswilligen'', lit. "[[European non-Germans in the German armed forces during World War II|those willing to help]]") for service with Nazi Germany in the [[General Government]]. His camp had also imprisoned [[Polish Jews]] condemned to slave labor. The Jews were all massacred in [[Operation Harvest Festival]] on 3 November 1943.<ref name="Jabłoński"/><ref name="Fischel">{{cite web | url=http://books.google.ca/books?id=EzBZP92xwUUC&lpg=PA265&dq=Trawniki&pg=PA264#v=onepage&q=Trawniki&f=false | title=Trawniki labor camp | publisher=Scarecrow Press | work=Historical Dictionary of the Holocaust | date=Jul 17, 2010 | accessdate=April 30, 2013 | author=Jack R. Fischel | pages=264&ndash;265 | isbn=0810874857 }}</ref><ref name="Niewyk-Nicosia">{{cite web | url=http://books.google.ca/books?id=nzJAXkfozW8C&lpg=PA210&dq=Trawniki&pg=PA210#v=onepage&q=Trawniki&f=false | title=Trawniki. A labor camp | publisher=Columbia University Press | work=The Columbia Guide to the Holocaust | year=2012 | accessdate=2013-04-30 | author=Donald L. Niewyk, Francis R. Nicosia | page=210 | isbn=0231528787}}</ref>
The ''[[Trawniki men]]'' (German: ''Trawnikimänner'') took part in [[Operation Reinhard]], the Nazi extermination of [[Polish Jews#The Holocaust: German-occupied Poland|Jews]]. They conducted executions at [[death camp]]s and in Jewish ghettos including [[Belzec]], [[Sobibor]], [[Treblinka extermination camp|Treblinka II]], [[Warsaw Ghetto|Warsaw]] (three times, see [[Stroop Report]]), [[Częstochowa Ghetto|Częstochowa]], [[Lublin Ghetto|Lublin]], [[Lvov Ghetto|Lwów]], [[Radom Ghetto|Radom]], [[Kraków Ghetto|Kraków]], [[Białystok Ghetto|Białystok]] (twice), [[Majdanek]] as well as at [[Auschwitz]], not to mention Trawniki itself,<ref name=USHMM1>{{cite web | url=http://www.ushmm.org/wlc/en/article.php?ModuleId=10007397 | title=Trawniki | publisher=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum | work=Holocaust Encyclopedia | accessdate=July 21, 2011}}</ref> and the remaining subcamps of KL Lublin/Majdanek including [[Poniatowa concentration camp|Poniatowa]], Budzyn, Kraśnik, Puławy, Lipowa, but also during massacres in [[Łomazy]], [[Międzyrzec Podlaski|Międzyrzec]], [[Łuków]], [[Radzyń Podlaski|Radzyń]], [[Parczew]], [[Końskowola]], [[Komarówka]] and all other locations, augmented by the ''SS'' and the [[Reserve Police Battalion 101]] from ''[[Ordnungspolizei#Police Battalions|Ordnungspolizei]]'' (Orpo).<ref name="Browning">{{cite web | url=http://hampshirehigh.com/exchange2012/docs/BROWNING-Ordinary%20Men.%20Reserve%20Police%20Battalion%20101%20and%20the%20Final%20Solution%20in%20Poland%20(1992).pdf | last=Browning | first=Christopher R. | author-link=Christopher Browning | year=1992–1998 | title=Arrival in Poland | publisher=Penguin Books | work=Ordinary Men: [[Reserve Police Battalion 101]] and the Final Solution in Poland | accessdate=May 1, 2013 | pages=52, 77, 79, 80 | format=PDF file, direct download 7.91 MB complete | quote=''Also:'' [http://www.webcitation.org/6GIJ2XpOy PDF cache archived by WebCite.]}}</ref><ref name="ARC">{{cite web | url=http://www.deathcamps.org/occupation/erntefest.html | title=Erntefest | publisher=ARC | work=Occupation of the East | year=2004 | accessdate=2013-04-26 | author=ARC}}</ref> {{further information|Jewish ghettos in German-occupied Poland|The Holocaust in Poland}}
==A free man== On 24 June 1944, Streibel escaped from Trawniki with his own ''[[SS Battalion Streibel]]'' toward [[Kraków]] and [[Auschwitz]], ahead of the Soviet offensive. They retreated again through Poland and Czechoslovakia to [[Dresden]], Germany, where his battalion was disbanded between 4 March and 12 April 1945. Streibel and his Hiwis blended in with the civilian population and disappeared from sight.<ref name="Black">{{cite web | url=http://books.google.ca/books?id=M7KbsHLnbwgC&pg=PA331&lpg=PA331&dq=Hamburg,++Karl++Streibel&source=bl&ots=snongsA_nf&sig=rPpoAZ4yJJckdezrIaZ8kGHP98g&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ol2rUdfJAdDDiwLD1IDQCQ&ved=0CDgQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=Hamburg%2C%20%20Karl%20%20Streibel&f=false | title=Police Auxiliaries for Operation Reinhard ''by'' Peter R. Black | publisher=Enigma Books | work=Secret Intelligence and the Holocaust | year=2006 | accessdate=2013-06-02 | author=David Bankir, ed | pages=331&ndash;348 | isbn=192963160X | format=Google Books}}</ref> Nothing was known about his whereabouts until his indictment in 1970. Streibel was put on trial in [[Hamburg]] for his wartime activities, and in 1976 acquitted of any wrongdoing and set free.<ref name="Hartmann">{{cite web | url=http://www.sopos.org/aufsaetze/4bdfd55e42f57/1.phtml | title=Der Alibiprozeß | publisher=Ossietzky 9/2010 | work=Den Aufsatz kommentieren | year=2010 | accessdate=2013-06-01 | author=Ralph Hartmann}}</ref> German prosecutor Helge Grabitz believed his word, but also granted him partial memory impairment.<ref name="Janson">{{cite web | url=http://www.matthiasjanson.de/arbeitsprobe_konkret2.html | title=Strafsache Trawniki | publisher=Matthias Janson | work=Veröffentlicht in konkret 11/2009, S. 38f. | year=2008 | accessdate=2013-06-01 | author=Matthias Janson}}</ref> Streibel was declared innocent of inciting violence; without prosecution right of appeal.<ref name="Hartmann" /><ref name="Partee">{{cite web | url=http://www.ukrainianstudies.uottawa.ca/pdf/P_Danyliw2011_Partee.pdf | title=Ukrainian Collaboration on Trial and the Trawniki Men Delivering Justice and Writing History | publisher=Clark University, Holocaust and Genocide Studies | work=Danyliw Research Seminar in Contemporary Ukrainian Studies | date=20–22 October 2011 | accessdate=2013-06-01 | author=Kimberly C. Partee | format=PDF file, direct download 126 KB}}</ref> Further accounts of his life appear missing.<ref name="Dixon">{{cite web | url=http://www.redcap70.net/A%20History%20of%20the%20SS%20Organisation%201924-1945.html/S/STREIBEL,%20Karl.html | title=Streibel, Karl | date=June 1990 | accessdate=2013-05-31 | author=Ian Dixon}}</ref>
